,"index":"00544","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And\nthat's all I have to say. I handed a handout; I wrote an article that's been\npublished. You know, I'm going to pretty well stop there, because the more I\nthink about it, the more adjectives I have that are inappropriate to describe\nthis act. And so I'll just leave it right there.","index":"00545","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou very much.","index":"00546","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Thank you, Mr. Sullivan, for your presentation.","index":"00547","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Do\nmembers of the committee have questions for the presenter?","index":"00548","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> Thank you, Mr. Sullivan, for your presentation, for taking time to\nbe with us this evening. I know it's been a long evening for many people, and\nwe appreciate you sticking it out and coming to give us those words, and we\ncertainly take them under advisement.","index":"00549","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"����� And\nI've spoken previously this evening about when we met with the grand chiefs and\nthe chiefs that were involved in those meetings, and this was one point of\ndiscussion. And TLE is not addressed in this particular act because it is\naddressed elsewhere, and we abide by it and we follow it and we have, indeed,\ntransferred more acres of land under TLE respon�sibilities than the previous\ngovernment ever did. ","index":"00550","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou. ","index":"00551","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nSullivan:</b> Yes, I'm not talking about treaty land; I'm talking about\nunoccupied Crown land. So, you sell unoccupied Crown land, you're infringing on\nsection&nbsp;35 rights. You're infringing on people's traplines. Yes, you are.\nDon't tell�shake your head at me, because I've been in this business a long\ntime. ","index":"00552","speaker":""},{"html":"����� If I\nwas First Nations, I'd be lining up with my lawyers in court and I'd be in a\nhuge battle with you folks because, you know what, I've seen you guys, and your\nidea of proper section 35 consultation leaves little to the imagination. ","index":"00553","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Brar:</b>\nThank you, Mr. Sullivan, for your presen�tation. ","index":"00554","speaker":"Diljeet Brar"},{"html":"����� Did\nyou get any chance to send any inputs for�during the consultation process? ","index":"00555","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nSullivan:</b> No, never been consulted. I talked to a number of First Nations\nthat I've known; they've never been consulted on this�these amendments to these\nsix&nbsp;acts. And they are unaware of the scope and nature of this wholesale\nselling of Crown assets.","index":"00556","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Are there any other questions from the floor? ","index":"00557","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Seeing\nnone, we will now�oh, Mr. Lindsey. ","index":"00558","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Tom Lindsey\n(Flin Flon):</b> Thank you for your presentation, Mr. Sullivan, and I can\nassure you that there are so many bad pieces of legislation that this\ngovernment is introducing and we're going to have a big job trying to repeal\neach and every one of them and get this province back on track. ","index":"00559","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� But I\nguess that's the mandate that we'll have is to fix everything that this bunch\nhas broken. ","index":"00560","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thanks.\n","index":"00561","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nSullivan:</b> Yes, I appreciate you confirming that you would repeal the\namendment to�or repeal Bill 12 in its entirety. I think it's absolutely a\nregressive piece of legislation that will literally sell the baby with the\nbathwater. ","index":"00562","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Are there any questions from the floor?","index":"00563","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Seeing\nnone, this concludes the time for ques�tioning. Thank you, Mr. Sullivan. ","index":"00564","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I will\nnow call on Mr. Fred Tait, private citizen, and we'll see if we can connect\nwith him via telephone. Stand by. ","index":"00565","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Mr.\nTait, if you can hear me, if you can unmute yourself by pressing *6 and then we\ncan hopefully hear your presentation this time. ","index":"00566","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Mr.\nTait, we actually can hear some noise, back�ground, but however, we cannot hear\nyour vocals. ","index":"00567","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Mr. Tait, we are still having the same issues. I am just\nwaiting for assistance from our technical staff.","index":"00568","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Ralph </b>","index":"00569","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>�(Minister\nof Economic Development and Jobs):</b> Mr. Chair, I wonder if there'd be leave\nof the committee if we could ask the Clerk's office to contact Mr. Tait and\nhave a presentation�that he write a presentation. It could not be entered into\nHansard, is my understanding, but it could be distributed to the members of the\ncommittee. ","index":"00570","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I\nwonder if that would be agreeable to the com�mittee. ","index":"00571","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Sure. Perhaps the Leg. staff could contact the gentleman and\nrecord an interview with him if he doesn't have the wherewithal to write a\nwritten statement and prevent�present that to the committee for consideration.\nSomething entirely new and different, but hey, this whole process is. ","index":"00572","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>*</b> (20:40)\n","index":"00573","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> <span lang=\"EN-US\">From the suggestion of the Honour�able\nMinister Eichler, is it the will of the committee to contact Mr. Tait given of\nthe nature of the technical difficulties that we're having, that the clerks\ncontact him so that he can provide a written presentation? And we all do\nunderstand that will�that it will not be included in Hansard? </span>","index":"00574","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">Is it the will of the committee to agree to that? <i>[Agreed]</i> </span>","index":"00575","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� I will now call on Chief Rod Travers to proceed with his\npresentation. But before I do that, I just want to say thank you for�Mr. Tait,\nfor his patience, and the committee is looking forward to your written presen�tation,\nand the clerks will contact you.</span>","index":"00576","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Chief Rod Travers from the Kinonjeoshtegon First Nation, if\nyou are on the line, please unmute yourself and turn your video on.</span>","index":"00577","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� Chief Travers is not present, so he will be\nstruck&nbsp;from the list. That concludes the list of presenters I have before\nme. </span>","index":"00578","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>* * *</b>","index":"00579","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> <span lang=\"EN-US\">In what order does the committee wish to\nproceed with clause-by-clause consideration of these bills? </span>","index":"00580","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nEichler:</b> We'll go in numerical order, is my suggestion, Mr. Chair. ","index":"00581","speaker":"Ralph Eichler"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Is it the will of the committee to proceed in numerical order?\n<i>[Agreed] </i>","index":"00582","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> We will now proceed with clause-by-clause of Bill 3, in\nnumerical order. ","index":"00583","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Does\nthe minister responsible for Bill 3 have an opening statement? ","index":"00584","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Reg Helwer\n(Minister of Central Services):</b> <span lang=\"EN-US\">I&nbsp;&nbsp;just have a\nfew words�comments in regards to Bill&nbsp;3. Thank you to everybody for their\npresentations tonight and for bringing forward a lot of information for us to\ncontinue�consider as we get ready to im�plement this new act and this\nframework, should it pass. </span>","index":"00585","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� If many of the presenters are still online, I hope to explain\na little bit about the process that we're going to go through now. We did have\nthe public presentations, and that's a very critical part of our committee\nprocess. We are now going to kind of move from the public process, although you\ncan still see it, to the legislative process, where we have to consider each\nclause of the written legislation, whether it passes or is not passed or is\namended, in order for the bill to be reported to the House, to the Legislature.\n</span>","index":"00586","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� So, it may go very fast, or it may go slow, but it will look a\nlittle bit foreign if you're not used to that type of�watching that role. So I\njust want to make sure that the comments that people made tonight, we certainly\ndo give them serious weight in the formulation of the bill and how it's\nenacted, and that they are certainly not ignored and we have staff that are\nmaking notes and will be giving me advice as we move ahead here. </span>","index":"00587","speaker":""},{"html":"<span lang=\"EN-US\">����� So, The Public Service Act will advance our public service\ninto the modern era. And it is a platform setting and articulates the role and\npurpose of the public service in serving Manitobans. The bill was crafted with\nthe understanding that time really does march on and transformation is one of the\nkeys to success. We know there is an ongoing necessity for the public service\nto reflect the times and in the environment in which it operates. I'm very\nproud that Bill 3 does this. It establishes a framework for an ethical and\neffective public service for Manitoba by setting out long-held principles and\nvalues, such as integrity and respect for others, to ensure that they are\nconsistently applied to the modern era. </span>","index":"00588","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nact also fosters alignment beyond our core government departments and across\nour public service and they will be guided by the principles and values in the\nact.","index":"00589","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Now,\nThe Public Service Act does include some transitional provisions which have\ntime restrictions or a time limit to�in order to facilitate the transition from\nold legislation to the new legislation, and we will be putting forward a couple\nof amendments to those transitional provisions tonight. I'm�apologize that I'm\nnot able to be in person there tonight due to some family issues, but Minister\nEichler, I believe, will be presenting them on my behalf there.","index":"00590","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So\nthank you, sincerely, to everyone that's in�volved in the legislative process\naround this important bill. It took a lot of time drafting, we know that, and\nlots of considerations moving it ahead.","index":"00591","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou, Mr. Chair. ","index":"00592","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> We thank the minister. ","index":"00593","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Does\nthe critic from the official opposition have an opening statement? ","index":"00594","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Tom Lindsey\n(Flin Flon):</b> Where is it? Okay, here we go.","index":"00595","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So,\nBill 3 replaces The Civil Service Act and creates three categories of civil servants:\nthe core public servants, the broader public service and the allied public\nservice. Most concerningly, Bill 3 elimi�nates the provisions for arbitration.","index":"00596","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nexisting Civil Service Act requires the minister to call an arbitration board\nupon request under section 48(1). MGEU requested arbitration in July 2019 and,\nby law, the minister should've established an arbitration panel within seven\ndays.","index":"00597","speaker":""},{"html":"����� MGEU\nhas been without a contract since March&nbsp;2019 and the Pallister government\nhas been trying to apply their unconstitutional bill 28. It took a decision of\nthe courts for the minister finally apply the law and allow arbitration.","index":"00598","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nminister clearly knew what the law meant. That's why now, after the fact,\nthey're introducing Bill&nbsp;3 to remove their legislative responsibility to\nappoint arbitration.","index":"00599","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nbill also dissolves the Civil Service Com�mission, replacing it with the Public\nService Commission. This is concerning because it removes a neutral and\narm's-length body which oversees the civil service.","index":"00600","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I note\nthat the government has put out requests for proposal to review the steps and\nlevels of compen�sation within the civil service. Such classification reviews\nshould only be done in a fair and transparent manner. Handing such functions to\nan external private consultant and then pulling back the autonomy of the Civil\nService Commission, as this bill does, that leads me to believe that the\nPallister government has ill intent here. ","index":"00601","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I warn\nthe minister that meddling with the Civil Service Commission and outsourcing\nclassification review is a recipe for disaster. The Pallister government is\nsetting up a major confrontation with its civil service.","index":"00602","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Bill 3\npoliticizes the public service and takes what are supposed to be two separate\nentities, the civil service and the ministers' offices, and blends them\ntogether. This decision opens up many opportunities for abuse of power and\nreverses a system that was carefully implemented in order to curb the potential\nfor political interference.","index":"00603","speaker":""},{"html":"����� With\nBill 3, the Pallister government is undoing a model for professional civil\nservice, opening the door for bad outcomes. ","index":"00604","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And I\nwish to thank all the presenters that were here for their patience in the\ntechnical difficulties and just for showing up to share their valuable input on\nBill 3. ","index":"00605","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I\nreally hope that the minister will listen to Manitobans and stop attacking\ntheir right to arbitration. Certainly, the presenters that were here tonight\nasked the minister to stop this bill, to reconsider what he's doing. So I would\nencourage the minister to really listen to what those presenters had to say.\nWithdraw this bill. ","index":"00606","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> We thank the member.","index":"00607","speaker":""},{"html":"����� During\nthe consideration of a bill, the preamble, the enacting clause and the title\nare postponed until all other clauses have been considered in their proper\norder. ","index":"00608","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Due to\nthe size and structure of this bill, the Chair�myself�would like to propose the\nfollowing order of consideration for the committee's consi�deration. For your\nreference, we will provide copies of this outline for committee members, with\nthe understanding that we may stop at any point where members have questions or\nwish to propose amend�ments. ","index":"00609","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(20:50)","index":"00610","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I\npropose that we call the bill in the following order: Part 1, comprising of\nclauses 1 to 3; part 2, comprising of clauses 4 and 5; part 3, comprising of\nclauses 6 to 31; part 4, comprising of clauses 32 and 33; part 5, comprising of\nclauses 34 to 41; part 6, comprising of clauses 42 to 51; part 7, comprising of\nclauses 52 to 55; part 8, comprising of clauses 56 to 60; part 9, comprising of\nclauses 61 to 64; part 10, comprising of clauses 65 to 138; part 11, comprising\nof clauses 139 to 141; the schedule; the preamble; the enacting clause; the\nbill title.","index":"00611","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Is that agreed as an appropriate order of consideration for Bill 3?\n<i>[Agreed]</i> ","index":"00612","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\npart 1, comprising of clauses 1 to 3, pass? ","index":"00613","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00614","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00615","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. Which clause would you like to speak to first? ","index":"00616","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> I would like to speak to clause 1 first. ","index":"00617","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 1 pass? ","index":"00618","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00619","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00620","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00621","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> So, just in the definitions, which is really what\nwe're talking about here, it talks about what the definition of pay is, and so\nmany of those things that it includes there are things that should be through\nthe collective bargaining process.","index":"00622","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So my\nquestion is: I wonder how things such as additional renumeration and allowances\nand bonuses and premiums�does that interfere with the collective bargaining\nprocess or is it merely an attempt to cobble everything together that may be\nincluded as pay, and does it affect it somewhere else down the road? ","index":"00623","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, the collective bargaining is not affected. ","index":"00624","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause 1�pass; clause 2�pass. ","index":"00625","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 3 pass? ","index":"00626","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00627","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait. Slow down.","index":"00628","speaker":""},{"html":"����� No. ","index":"00629","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b>\nShall clause 3 pass? ","index":"00630","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> No. ","index":"00631","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00632","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> So, there's all sorts of parts and pieces in this\nthat cover various aspects. It talks about things such as merit. It talks about\nthe mobility of the operate�workers within the department. ","index":"00633","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So my questions are: (1) does this in any way impact the rights of\nunion members when it comes to seniority? When we talk about merit for\nappointments of the core public service, they ought to be made free from\npolitical influence, but merit won't necessarily do that; what does that is\nseniority clauses that are fundamental to unions. ","index":"00634","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The other question I have is around the mobility. Does this mean\nthat civil service workers will be expected to bounce from department to\ndepartment rather than having departments fully staffed and able to perform\ntheir functions properly? Will workers be moved around constantly and never\nknow exactly where they're supposed to be working?","index":"00635","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nnext question I would have would be around the classification plan that the\nminister must establish and maintain. Those kind of things should probably be\nnegotiated, not just driven by the minister. ","index":"00636","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Mr. Lindsey, are your questions directed to clause 3 or part\n3? ","index":"00637","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Good question. Probably part 3. ","index":"00638","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Mr. Lindsey, we're currently on clause 3. ","index":"00639","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> All right, I'll back up. My apologies. ","index":"00640","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Mr. Lindsey, go ahead. ","index":"00641","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> Then it should pass. ","index":"00642","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b>\nClause 3�pass.","index":"00643","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Part\n2, comprising of clauses 4 and 5�pass.","index":"00644","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\npart 3, comprising of clauses 6 to 31, pass? ","index":"00645","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00646","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00647","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00648","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause are you�would you like to speak on first? ","index":"00649","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> First, I would like to speak on clause 8, where it talks about the\nprinciples of diversity, inclusion, fairness, merit and mobility. ","index":"00650","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clauses 6 and 7�pass.","index":"00651","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 8 pass? ","index":"00652","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00653","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00654","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00655","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> My questions are around a couple of things in clause 8. The first\nis around the principle that is expounded here on merit. ","index":"00656","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� My\nquestion is: does the merit provision override the principle of seniority?","index":"00657","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And\nwhile this provision talks about appointment to the core public service ought\nto be made on merit and free from political influence, the surest way to ensure\nthat is to follow seniority, as opposed to merit, where somebody decides I like\nyou, I don't like you, and that's how people get appointed.","index":"00658","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So,\ndoes this override the principles of seniority? ","index":"00659","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, as I see here, seniority and its appli�cations is generally\nnegotiated between the union and an employer, and that's not a matter that's\ntypically legislated. Nothing in The Public Service Act prevents the government\nand its unions from negotiating seniority provisions or, in the case of\nexcluded em�ployees, a non-bargaining unit, the government from enacting\nprocesses and policies that recognize length and�of service. ","index":"00660","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> I recognize that seniority is something that's negotiated by the\nunions and the employer, but specifically, when you add a clause in to this\nthat talks specifically about merit, it leaves the door open for favouritism\nand all kinds of other issues that seniority was developed to override those\nconcerns. And I didn't hear the minister say that the overriding principle for\nappointments and promotions and all the rest of it will be seniority first and\nmerit second. ","index":"00661","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> I think if the member has patience and lets us get to, say, 12(2),\nhe will see where that is addressed. ","index":"00662","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> I have an abundance of patience. I hope the minister does, because\nwe're going to be here a while, but�so, I'll wait for that part. But then my\nnext question is around mobility.","index":"00663","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So we\nknow that there's already a shortage in many departments with people working\nthere. Does the provision now being put in here about mobility mean that people\nthat work for the civil service or whatever it is we're calling them these\ndays�does that mean they may be working in one department today, another\ndepartment tomorrow, and be bouncing all over the place�which leads to less\naccountability, less knowledge, less service to the public.","index":"00664","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So, is\nthat what's happening here with this mobility, that the minister's\ncontemplating being able to employ less workers and just moving them all over\nthe place? ","index":"00665","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, mobility, in terms of this act, is very aspirational. It's a\nprinciple. It's about supporting the professional development of our civil\nservice. It will not direct people to different jobs. ","index":"00666","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, clause&nbsp;8�pass.","index":"00667","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 9 to 31 pass? ","index":"00668","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00669","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00670","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b> (21:00)","index":"00671","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. Which clause would you like to speak on first,\nMr. Lindsey? ","index":"00672","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Clause 9. ","index":"00673","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 9 pass? ","index":"00674","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00675","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00676","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00677","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> When we're talking about the classification right now, I'm\nassuming that that classification plan for how workers get paid within the\ncivil service has been developed in consultation with unions over the years and\nis a plan that really works for everyone; but now it says the minister must\nestablish and maintain a classification plan for positions in the core public\nservice. ","index":"00678","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� Does\nthat mean that the minister will be deciding and developing the classification\nplan without involving the workers' representatives, the unions, in the\nestablishment of the classification plan?� ","index":"00679","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> No. ","index":"00680","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, clause&nbsp;9�pass.","index":"00681","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 10 to 31 pass? ","index":"00682","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00683","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00684","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00685","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause would you like to speak on, Mr.&nbsp;Lindsey? ","index":"00686","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Clause 10. ","index":"00687","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 10 accordingly pass? ","index":"00688","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00689","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00690","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions.� ","index":"00691","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Again, it's�the minister must establish policies about all these\ndifferent things: a diverse and inclusive workforce, respectful workplace,\nemployee conflict of interest, workforce planning. Those are all good things\nthat should be developed and put in place, but they should be developed in\nconsultation with unions and the workers that are involved there. ","index":"00692","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� Is\nthat the intent of the minister, to develop those policies in collaboration,\nconsultation and agreement with the various unions that may represent those\nworkers? ","index":"00693","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> That is some of the processes we do undertake. I know from watching\nthe previous NDP&nbsp;government, they fled from responsibility, and I&nbsp;witnessed\nit several times. But the minister is ultimately responsible. ","index":"00694","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, clause 10�pass. ","index":"00695","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 11 to 31 pass? ","index":"00696","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00697","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00698","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00699","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause would you like to speak on first? ","index":"00700","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Clause 11. ","index":"00701","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 11 pass? ","index":"00702","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00703","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00704","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear an no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00705","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> It talks about the commissioner must develop and implement\npolicies for recruitment, flexible work, accommodation. ","index":"00706","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So,\nonce upon a time there was a Civil Service Commission. Now there's merely a\ncommissioner that's appointed by the government. So, they've got all this power\nnow in the commissioner's hand and, again, it doesn't talk anything about\ndeveloping any of these policies in consultation with the unions, the workers,\nbecause we've done away with the commission that was quasi-independent. Now,\nit's strictly the govern�ment that's going to develop these things like\nflexible work arrangements, including hours of work and settings of work. ","index":"00707","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So, is\nit the minister's intent to involve the union in those discussions and\nnegotiate these things into being? Or is it his desire to have the commissioner\nmerely mandate them? ","index":"00708","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> This supports the non-partisan piece of the legislation by putting\nthe administrative policies into the purview of the public service commission.\nSection 12(2) still applies, so where negotiation would be required, yes, it\nwould�we would negotiate. ","index":"00709","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no other questions, clause&nbsp;11�pass. ","index":"00710","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 12 to 31 pass? ","index":"00711","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00712","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Wait; wait, wait, wait, wait. No. ","index":"00713","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> �Shall clauses 12 to 31 pass? ","index":"00714","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00715","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00716","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00717","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause would you like to speak on, Mr.&nbsp;Lindsey? ","index":"00718","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Very briefly on clause 12(2).","index":"00719","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 12(2) pass? <i>[interjection]</i> Correction:\nshall clause 12 pass?","index":"00720","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00721","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00722","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b>\nI hear a no. The floor is open for questions.","index":"00723","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> So, just my question to the ministers around 12(2): Despite\nsubsection (1), the terms and conditions of employment for represented\nemployees may be established by a collective agreement.","index":"00724","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So I\njust want to confirm that the collective agreement will take precedence and be\nthe guiding principle, as opposed to a regulation that may offer something less\nthan or anything that applies to those people covered by the collective\nagreement, that the collective agreement overrides legislation unless the\nlegislation offers something greater than. ","index":"00725","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So,\nbasically, whichever one offers either the best protection or the greatest\nbenefit would be the one that applies, not necessarily just the legislated\nrequire�ment.","index":"00726","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> Perhaps if I read the clause, it may be clear. I'm not sure how to\nanswer his question any other way. ","index":"00727","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"����� Despite\nsubsection (1), the terms and conditions of employment for represented\nemployees may be established by a collective agreement. If a term or condition\nof the collective agreement is inconsistent with a term or condition\nestablished by regulation, then the term or condition in the collective\nagreement applies to the represented employees. ","index":"00728","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Are there any other questions?","index":"00729","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Yes, I read that too. I just want to make sure that the union has\nthe ability to negotiate things over and above what's in the legislation or the\nact, to ensure that they're covered by doing that.","index":"00730","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> The collective agreement, as it says there, applies; it prevails. I\ndon't know how to be any clearer than that, than what it says in black and\nwhite there. ","index":"00731","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no other�seeing no further questions, clause 12�pass.","index":"00732","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 13 through 31 pass?","index":"00733","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable\nMembers:</b> Pass.","index":"00734","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00735","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00736","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause would you like to speak on, specifically?","index":"00737","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Fourteen.","index":"00738","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause 13�pass.","index":"00739","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 14 pass? ","index":"00740","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00741","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00742","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause�I hear a no. The floor is open for questions.","index":"00743","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> So, when we're talking about the competitive process, the policies\nfor recruitment and selection must provide for a competitive process designed\nto establish the merit of candidates. The factors to be considered in merit\ninclude education, skills, knowledge, experience and competencies.","index":"00744","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� Is\nthere a ranking factor when it comes to determining the merit factor? So, it\ntalks very broadly about all these things that go into the merit, but does�is\nthere like a point system that says education, you get this many points;\nexperience, you get that many points; seniority, you get a certain number of\npoints; or is it just vaguely encapsulated in it?","index":"00745","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Minister Helwer? Go ahead, Minister Helwer.","index":"00746","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, The Civil Service Act contemplates merit. I'm not sure if the\nmember's ever applied for a civil service position, but there are, you know, a\nvariety of ways that points are attributed to various areas. ","index":"00747","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"����� In\nterms of how we run a competitive process with interviews and such, there are a\nlot of factors that are at play and not all of them are black and white.","index":"00748","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> To answer the minister's question: no, I&nbsp;&nbsp;have never\napplied for a civil service position, but I &nbsp;have applied for positions in\nthe private sector where it was clearly spelled out through the negotiation\nprocess how all these different aspects were consi�dered in awarding jobs for\npeople, and experience, seniority, was one of the guiding principles. And these\nother things kind of went along with it, but there was a ranking system for\neach one of those that allowed people to know that the system was fair and\nopen. ","index":"00749","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(21:10)","index":"00750","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Is\nthat a similar system to what's contemplated or what's in place now? ","index":"00751","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, if I can go back to 12(2): Despite subsection (1), the terms\nand conditions of employ�ment for represented employees may be established by a\ncollective agreement. If a term or condition of the collective agreement is\ninconsistent with a term or condition established by regulation, then the term\nor condition in the collective agreement applies to the represented employees.","index":"00752","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, clause&nbsp;14�pass.","index":"00753","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 15 to 31 pass? ","index":"00754","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00755","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00756","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. Which clause would you like to�","index":"00757","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Fifteen. ","index":"00758","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Okay.","index":"00759","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 15 pass? ","index":"00760","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable\nMembers:</b> Pass. ","index":"00761","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00762","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause�I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00763","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> We're talking about direct appoint�ments in clause 15(2), and it\nsays that the com�missioner, who now is really someone appointed directly by\nthe government�there's no commission anymore that has the separation, if you\nwill�so it talks about the individual who can be appointed has specialized\nskills, knowledge and experience�I get that�the urgency of staffing requirements\nrenders the competitive process impracticable and direct appointment is\nnecessary for effective deployment of workforce resources.","index":"00764","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� That\nseems that this commissioner now has way too much power to tell employees,\nwell, I'm hiring somebody to fill this position rather than using the&nbsp;&nbsp;normal\nbulletin procedure that would allow employees to progress and use their skills\nand keep learning new skills. And the direct appointment is necessary for\neffective deployment is really what concerns me the most because it's kind of a\ncatch-all phrase that this commissioner, at the direction of the minister, no\ndoubt, could use for directly appointing people in positions all over the place\nwith no real reason for doing that.","index":"00765","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So is\nthere anything that's going to spell out in more detail these clauses so that\npeople have some understanding and comfort with them? Because right now it just\nseems like this commissioner is the powerful Oz behind the curtain. ","index":"00766","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, again, I go back to the collective agreements. But perhaps, I\ndon't know, the member hasn't been paying attention to the last year and a half\nof what's happening. During the pandemic, we used this several times. You know,\nyou have to have people with the knowledge and ability to do the things that we\nneeded done in a very quick time frame. And that would be a great example of\nwhen you might use a direct appointment. They are still subject to all the\nother areas, and they must be qualified. ","index":"00767","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> I guess the pandemic is a great example of an emergency that would\nrequire�but this doesn't just talk about emergencies that might require; this\ntalks about for effective deployment of workforce resources. So I'm short\nstaffed in one department; I'm going to take people and direct them that now,\ntoday, you're working in this department. And we know already that the\ngovernment is short staffed in so many departments. So just kind of robbing\nPeter to pay Paul is not going to be the right answer, and yet that's exactly\nwhat this particular provision will allow. ","index":"00768","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So is\nthere anything that will really spell out when this commissioner would be able\nto exercise these great powers that they're going to have? Is it just for an\nemergency situation, or is it every day of the week, just in somebody's\ndetermination of effective deployment of workforce resources, as it says here? ","index":"00769","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> Again, I think a thorough reading of all the words there answers\nthe question. It's pretty clear to me when and how this might be applied. You\nknow, there are circumstances in certain areas of the province where we might\nfind difficulty filling a position, and that might be one way or one time that\nthis might be used. But it talks about�well, again, reading the clause, I\nthink, makes it clear. ","index":"00770","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, shall clause 15 pass? ","index":"00771","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00772","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00773","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> On division. ","index":"00774","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause 15 is passed, on division. ","index":"00775","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 16 to 31 pass?","index":"00776","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00777","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clauses� ","index":"00778","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> No. ","index":"00779","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no.","index":"00780","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause would you like to specifically speak on, Mr. Lindsey? ","index":"00781","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Oh, let's start at clause 20. ","index":"00782","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clauses 16 to 19�pass. ","index":"00783","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 20 pass? ","index":"00784","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00785","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00786","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00787","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Well, really, for me to talk about clause&nbsp;20, I have to talk\nabout 21 as well and 22; they're all kind of tied in together as to suspension\nfor cause. ","index":"00788","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So,\nthe commissioner, again, seems to have this superpower to start laying people\noff based on their decisions around the performance, but there's really nothing\nthat spells that out anywhere as to what exactly just cause will be. ","index":"00789","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Is it\nstrictly the commissioner's opinion, or will there will�be something�and I get\nthat it�a union or a worker that has a union will obviously have the grievance\nprocedure and all the rest of it to go through, but what about workers that\ndon't have a union? What will their recourse be when the commissioner just\ndecides today that, yes, you're gone; we don't need you anymore? ","index":"00790","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, I hope you're not equating layoffs to just cause. I don't think\nthey're equal. But I think if you go down to clause 23, matters dealt with by\nthe collective agreement, the discipline, suspension, dismissal or layoff of a\nrepresented employee must be dealt with in accordance with the applicable\ncollective agreement if provided for in the agreement.","index":"00791","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> If the minister had listened to my question, I said I realized\nthat people that are represented by a union will have recourse, but what about\nemployees that are not represented by a union? What is their recourse when the\ncommissioner, the all-powerful commissioner, decides to suspend them and says\nit's with cause? ","index":"00792","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, the excluded employees that the member refers to have the same\nrights in common law as other employees, and the act�and�that the act gives\nthem, and clause 31 allows us to put that into regulations. ","index":"00793","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Soon, soon enough. I'll move on from that. ","index":"00794","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing that there are no further questions, clause 20�pass. ","index":"00795","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 21 to 31 pass? ","index":"00796","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00797","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00798","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no.","index":"00799","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause? ","index":"00800","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Twenty-one. ","index":"00801","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. Floor is open for questions on clause 21. <i>[interjection]</i>\nShall clause 21 pass? ","index":"00802","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00803","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00804","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause 21�oh, I hear a no.","index":"00805","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Go\nahead, Mr. Lindsey. ","index":"00806","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> So we've talked a little bit about suspension and dismissal for\ncause, but now we're getting into grounds for dismissal without cause. ","index":"00807","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So,\nagain, this all-powerful commissioner or a deputy minister can start dismissing\npublic service employees without cause simply by giving them notice. Somehow\nthis seems to be an overreach on the part of the government that just because\nthey don't like somebody they're going to get rid of them without cause. And,\nyes, they may have to pay them some severance pay, but it seems that without\nthe commission there anymore, with just this all-powerful commissioner, that\nthat power and authority is vested in one individual who's pointed�appointed\nstrictly by the government, and there doesn't seem to be the oversight that\nthere should be to protect people that work in the civil service.� ","index":"00808","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(21:20)","index":"00809","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, Mr. Lindsey�or Mr. Chair, sorry�so this currently exists in The\nCivil Service Act,<b> </b>and we already have rights as an employer to manage\nstaff, including performance and discipline. ","index":"00810","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Do you have any other questions, Mr. Lindsey? No? ","index":"00811","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Seeing\nno further questions, shall clause 21 pass? ","index":"00812","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00813","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00814","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00815","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> On division. ","index":"00816","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause 21 passes, on division. ","index":"00817","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 22 to 31 pass? ","index":"00818","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00819","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00820","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00821","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Which\nclause? ","index":"00822","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> Twenty-two. ","index":"00823","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 22 pass? ","index":"00824","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00825","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00826","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00827","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Again, it seems that the 