this. ","index":"00849","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I see no other questions. ","index":"00850","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Clause\n31�pass; part 4, comprising of clauses 32 and 33�pass.","index":"00851","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\npart 5, comprising of clauses 34 to 41 pass?","index":"00852","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00853","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00854","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no.","index":"00855","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Let the minister go first because he's probably going to amend\nwhat I'm going to ask questions about. ","index":"00856","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause 34�pass. ","index":"00857","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclauses 35 to 41 pass? ","index":"00858","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00859","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No.","index":"00860","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00861","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 35 pass? ","index":"00862","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00863","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00864","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00865","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> My questions are around the entire political activities that it�it\nseems painful to go through this clause by clause to bring up, really, a lot of\nthe same questions, but that's the system we have, so I guess that's where we\nare. ","index":"00866","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So,\nthe purpose of this part is to recognize the rights of employees to engage in\npolitical activities while maintaining the principle of political impar�tiality\nin the core public service. And I guess I don't so much have a problem with\nclause 35 as I do with everything that comes after it that really starts\ngetting in the way of people's ability to become political.","index":"00867","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So,\ncan the minister assure us that it's not the government's intention in any way,\nshape or form to prevent a member of the public service from running for\npolitical office?","index":"00868","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> I think I can pretty much give you confidence that political\nactivities were contemplated in this CSA, but this clarifies it a little bit\nmore. ","index":"00869","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"����� I did\nhave a circumstance of a civil servant that was helping me in a campaign and\nhis director was questioned by an NDP minister, if that employee was using any\ngovernment resources or if the employee's activity working with me impaired his\nwork for the director. And I think that's definitely grounds for a harassment\nclaim under our current situation, and those are the types of things that we\nwant to avoid.","index":"00870","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I\nthink it was absolutely untoward of that NDP minister to make that request of\nthe director and it certainly made that employee feel very uncomfortable and\nquestioned the intent of the minister. ","index":"00871","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, clause&nbsp;35�pass; clause\n36�pass.","index":"00872","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 37 pass? ","index":"00873","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00874","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00875","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00876","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> In clause 37(2), on receiving the employee's request, the deputy\nminister must grant the employee a leave of absence without pay for any part of\nthe period before the election that the deputy minister considers appropriate.","index":"00877","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� How\ndoes the deputy minister get to decide what's appropriate for the person taking\nleave? Should it not be the candidate or should there not be some sort of\nimpartial body that makes that determination? It's a civil servant that's\nrunning for the political party that I happen to be a part of, so as deputy\nminister, I give them more time off; if it's somebody that's potentially\nrunning in opposition maybe they get less time off. It really comes down to the\ndeputy minister considering what's appropriate. That somehow seems like maybe\nthere should be something spelled out in regulation <span lang=\"EN-US\">that\ndetermines the appropriate lengths of time for candidates�depending on various\nelection periods and nomination periods and all the rest of it�as opposed to\njust leaving it up to the deputy minister to decide, no, you can only have a\nweek off, when in reality you should be getting a month off. </span>","index":"00878","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(21:30)","index":"00879","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> This is also drawn from The Civil Service Act. ","index":"00880","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> So there's probably things, as you've pointed out,\nMr. Minister, that need to be updated within the current act and we've never\nonce said there are things that shouldn't be updated. ","index":"00881","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� And maybe this is one of the things that needs some attention in\nthe current act, as opposed to throwing the current act out and bringing in\nthis wholesale change. ","index":"00882","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> We drew the things from The Civil Service Act that were working\nwell and we modified those that we had to modernize. This is one that we drew\nacross from The Civil Service Act in its�as�excuse me�as it exists. ","index":"00883","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, clause&nbsp;37�pass.\n","index":"00884","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall clauses 38 to 41 pass? ","index":"00885","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00886","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00887","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> I hear a no.","index":"00888","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Clause 38�pass; clause 39�pass.","index":"00889","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 40 pass? ","index":"00890","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00891","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00892","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00893","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> So, an employee ceases to be employee on the day the\nemployee is declared elected. I know in the private sector, for example, when I\nwas first running for an MLA position, my job was guaranteed upon my either not\nbeing elected or the term of office ceasing to be. ","index":"00894","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� I'm\nwondering why civil servants are treated less, that if they run for an elected\noffice, they don't have a job to come back to. ","index":"00895","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, if someone wins an election, that is seen as a change of\nemployment. ","index":"00896","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> But there should be provisions in there that, when their term for\nthe elected office, if they no longer��if they don't win the next election,\nthey choose not to run�that their job is still there. ","index":"00897","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� It is\nin private sector. I know, certainly, in the workplace I came out of, it was\nthere. Now, that was&nbsp;&nbsp;something that was negotiated by the union and&nbsp;&nbsp;maybe\nthe unions representing civil servants have negotiated something in a\ncollective agreement around this. ","index":"00898","speaker":""},{"html":"����� But\nagain, it seems to limit an employee's ability to run for political office\nthat, if they are successful, and in four years, or three years, or two years,\ndepending on what a certain Premier decides to do, all of a sudden they get\nunelected and now they don't have a job to go back to. That just seems wrong. ","index":"00899","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> I think the member has answered his own question. It may be\nencompassed in a collective agreement and this does not override the collective\nagreement. ","index":"00900","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> And as much as I wish every working person belonged\nto a union, they don't. So, to put something specifically in an act that\ninhibits a person's ability to run for political office seems probably\nunconstitutional.","index":"00901","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So I\nwould suggest that that provision should be removed. ","index":"00902","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Helwer:</b> I hope the member's not sugges�ting that we hold a\nposition for someone who is perhaps the length of term of a Mr. Maloway, for\ninstance. I do know that there are other members that were elected and their\nprovisions and their collective agreements were that they had a time limit.\nOften, it was two terms. If the individual was elected a third term, then they\ndidn't have rights to come back to that employer. So, it really does depend on\nthe collective agreement. ","index":"00903","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Well, I guess I was very fortunate to have a strong union that\nnegotiated something for me, because there was no length associated with it. My\nemployer, I guess, recognized the importance of democracy in allowing their\nemployees to take part in it.","index":"00904","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� And,\nreally, I think I find this particular clause undemocratic, to say the least.� ","index":"00905","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> I think we're going to have to agree to disagree on this one. The\ncollective agreements are the ones that will determine the length of that.\nWe're not going to override the collective agreement with this clause. ","index":"00906","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, shall clause 40 pass? ","index":"00907","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass.","index":"00908","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00909","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clause�I hear a no. ","index":"00910","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An\nHonourable Member:</b> A recorded vote.","index":"00911","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00912","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Voice Vote</b>","index":"00913","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> All those in favour of clause 40, please say aye.","index":"00914","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Aye.","index":"00915","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> All those opposed, please say nay.","index":"00916","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Nay.","index":"00917","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> In my opinion, the Ayes have it. ","index":"00918","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Clause\n40 is�the�clause 40 is accordingly passed. <i>[interjection]</i> ","index":"00919","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Recorded Vote</b>","index":"00920","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Now, a recorded vote, please.","index":"00921","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> A recorded vote has been requested. ","index":"00922","speaker":""},{"html":"����� For\nthe information of the�all members of the committee, recorded votes will take\nplace in a similar way to those in the Chamber.� ","index":"00923","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><i>A\nCOUNT-OUT VOTE</i></b><i> was taken, the result being as follows: Yeas 3, Nays\n2.</i> ","index":"00924","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Clause 40 is accordingly passed. ","index":"00925","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>* * *</b>","index":"00926","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Clause\n41�pass; part 6, comprising of clauses 42 to 51�pass. ","index":"00927","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b>\nShall�<i>[interjection]</i> ","index":"00928","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Recorded Vote</b>","index":"00929","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Okay, we will revert back to clause 40 for the recorded vote,\nas the recorded vote has been requested. ","index":"00930","speaker":""},{"html":"����� For\nthe information of all members of the committee, recorded votes will take place\nin a similar way to those in the Chamber. ","index":"00931","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><i>A\nCOUNT-OUT VOTE</i></b><i> was taken, the result being as follows: Yeas 3, Nays\n2.</i> ","index":"00932","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Clause 40 is accordingly passed. ","index":"00933","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>* * *</b>","index":"00934","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Shall clause 41�shall part seven, comprising of clauses 52 to\n55, pass? ","index":"00935","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00936","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00937","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no.","index":"00938","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Clause\n52�pass. ","index":"00939","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 53 pass? ","index":"00940","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00941","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00942","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions.","index":"00943","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(21:40)","index":"00944","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Well, I look at this part, where we're talking about consultation\nand collaboration, and it clearly says the clerk of the Executive Council and\nthe commissioner may consult and collaborate with employers and establish a\ncouncil of employers, but nowhere in here does it ever say they're going to\nconsult with their workers, their unions, the people that represent, which\nseems�how the heck are we ever going to have a consistent, co-ordinated\napproach to ensuring ethical and effective public services if we don't involve\nthe people that are expected to carry out those duties?","index":"00945","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� We're\ngoing to consult and collaborate with employers and form an employers' council.\nLet's consult with the unions that represent those workers. ","index":"00946","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So why\nis that part not included in here, in the consultation part? ","index":"00947","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> So, the various organizations can consult with the unions, and that\nis the consultation process. It would be improper for us to consult on behalf of\nthose broader public sector organizations. I think they would see it as a clear\nintervention into their rights and responsibilities. ","index":"00948","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Well, I go�guess, if you're going to individual employees to\nconsult, which I'm sure somewhere else in here it does talk about some of that,\nbut I'd be surprised if the unions representing people that work in the civil\nservice would be opposed to consulting and collaborating on ways to make the\ncivil service better. It just seems to fly in the face of the whole point of\nwhat you've suggested here in this part. You're going to consult with everybody\nexcept for the people that represent the workers.","index":"00949","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� So I'd\nsuggest, again, that perhaps maybe you should relook at this part, because it\nseems to be missing the boat. ","index":"00950","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> It's a little disturbing to me that the member doesn't like\ncollective agreements. I�he�both in clause 40 and here he wants us to ignore\ncollective agreements, and we can't do that. ","index":"00951","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Well, unfortunately, the minister is confused. He's confused in\nwhat I asked him to do. He's confused in the concept of consultation and\ncollaboration. There's nothing that would go against a collective agreement to\nsit down with a union and discuss things. ","index":"00952","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� When I\nwas a union representative, we sat and consulted and discussed any number of\nissues. It didn't interfere with collective bargaining. In fact, some�times we\nnegotiated and discussed and came up with letters of understanding outside the\ncollective agreement because something came up that hadn't been contemplated at\nthe time the collective agreement was negotiated, which worked for the\nbetterment of everybody. It made a better workplace; it made for better\nemployees.","index":"00953","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So I\ndon't see where consultation and colla�boration with the union is contrary to\ncollective bargaining principles, but the minister seems to be confused about\nwhat consultation means. And maybe that's the root cause of the problem here. ","index":"00954","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nHelwer:</b> Well, perhaps we can go back to Hansard, but I distinctly recall\nthe question being consulting with employees, not unions. ","index":"00955","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Seeing no further questions, shall clause 53 pass? ","index":"00956","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00957","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00958","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00959","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Voice Vote</b>","index":"00960","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> All those in favour, please say aye.","index":"00961","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Aye.","index":"00962","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> All those in favour, please say nay.","index":"00963","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Nay.","index":"00964","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> In my opinion, the Ayes have it.","index":"00965","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Recorded Vote</b>","index":"00966","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> A recorded vote. ","index":"00967","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> A recorded vote has been requested. ","index":"00968","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><i>A\nCOUNT-OUT VOTE</i></b><i> was taken, the result being as follows: Yeas 3, Nays\n3. </i>","index":"00969","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Clause 53 is accordingly passed. ","index":"00970","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>* * *</b>","index":"00971","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Clauses 54 to 55�pass. ","index":"00972","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\npart 8, comprising of clauses 56 to 60 pass? ","index":"00973","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00974","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00975","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00976","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall\nclause 56 pass? ","index":"00977","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Pass. ","index":"00978","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00979","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> I hear a no. The floor is open for questions. ","index":"00980","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b>\nSo my quick question is: clause 56(1) where it talks about the appointment of\nthe Clerk at the Legislative Assembly. The Lieutenant Governor-in-Council must\nappoint and fix renumeration of the Clerk of the Leg. Assembly","index":"00981","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� Who\ndoes that now? ","index":"00982","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Helwer:</b>\nAgain, this is drawn from The Civil Service Act, so it is done this way now. ","index":"00983","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> Is that position not appointed and the&nbsp;&nbsp;renumeration set\nby the Legislative Assembly Management Commission? ","index":"00984","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Helwer:</b> I do not believe so. ","index":"00985","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> Can the minister\ntell us which section of the current act says this? ","index":"00986","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Helwer:</b> I think we'll have to\nget the exact clause from the previous act, if the member wants that. I don't\nknow if he�I don't know. I just don't know how to respond or why you need the particular\nclause from the previous act. If we drew it from that act, is it not&nbsp;&nbsp;sufficient?\nYou want the side-by-side during committee here? I'm kind of lost on this one.\nCan I�can the member please help me out?","index":"00987","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>*</b> (21:50)","index":"00988","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Seeing no\nfurther questions, clause&nbsp;56�pass; clauses 57 to 60�pass. ","index":"00989","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall part 9, comprising of\nclauses 61 to 64, pass? ","index":"00990","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable Members:</b> No. ","index":"00991","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> I hear a no. The\nHonourable Minister Eichler. <i>[interjection]</i> ","index":"00992","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>����� </b>Clause 61�pass; clause\n62�pass; clause 63�pass. ","index":"00993","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall clause 64 pass?","index":"00994","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An Honourable Member:</b> No. ","index":"00995","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> I hear a no. ","index":"00996","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Ralph Eichler (Minister of\nEconomic Development and Jobs):</b> I move ","index":"00997","speaker":"Ralph Eichler"},{"html":"<i>THAT Clause 64(5) of the Bill be\namended by striking out \"not represented by a bargaining agent (as that\nterm is defined in The Labour Relations Act) or excluded from a bargaining\nunit\".</i>","index":"00998","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><i>Motion presented.</i></b> ","index":"00999","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> The amendment is\nin order. The floor is open for questions.� ","index":"01000","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> I'd just like some\nclarification on what the purpose of this amendment is and what its intended\nconsequences are. ","index":"01001","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Helwer:</b> To go back to the\nmember's previous question, we can clarify for him that that clause, it was\nunder 32(a) of The Civil Service Act and now this portion here allows all\nemployees to continue to use the existing board process for appeals in a\nprocess when the act is proclaimed. So, if those appeals are�have started, they\nwill continue through the appeal process with the board. If there is something\nafter the proclamation of the act, then it would follow a different process. ","index":"01002","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Lindsey:</b> So, just so I\nunderstand exactly, right now the way you've worded the act itself or the Bill\n3 is that if something that had started before this came into being would carry\non for an employee not represented by a bargaining agent and by your removal of\n\"not represented by a bargaining agent\" it treats all employees the\nsame now that if something had been commenced before this comes into being,\nthat that carries on. Is that correct? ","index":"01003","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Helwer:</b> I think, if I listen\nto his verbiage, that that is correct. If someone appeals today and the act is,\nlet's say, passed tomorrow, that appeal would follow the current process as\nopposed to a new process, so it's not orphaned; it's not abandoned. It\ncontinues in the current situation that just enables that. ","index":"01004","speaker":"Reg Helwer"},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Seeing no\nfurther questions, is the committee ready for the question? ","index":"01005","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable Members:</b> Question.\n","index":"01006","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> The question for\nthe committee is as follows: ","index":"01007","speaker":""},{"html":"<i>THAT Clause 64(5) of the Bill be\namended by striking out \"not represented by a bargaining agent (as that\nterm is defined in The Labour Relations Act) or excluded from a bargaining unit\"</i>.","index":"01008","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An Honourable Member:</b> Dispense.","index":"01009","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Amendment�pass.","index":"01010","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Shall clause 64 pass, as amended?","index":"01011","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>An Honourable Member:</b> No.","index":"01012","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> Shall clause 64\nas amended pass?","index":"01013","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some Honourable Members:</b> No.","index":"01014","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Chairperson:</b> I hear a no.","index":"01015","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Eichler:</b> I move�� ","index":"01016","speaker":"Ralph Eichler"},{"html":"<i>THAT the following be added after Clause\n64(6) of the Bill:</i>","index":"01017","speaker":""},{"html":"<i>Exception � appeal to</i> <i>commission</i>\n","index":"01018","speaker":""},{"html":"<i>Reference\nto</i> the <i>commission in</i> a <i>collective agreement </i>","index":"01019","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nChairperson:</b> Can the minister please repeat and resay the amendment?","index":"01020","speake